  "title" : "Is there a way to run Eclipse clean up without using the GUI, aka in headless mode?",
  "body" : "<p>I'm looking for a way to apply Eclipse Java cleanup rules (not just code formatting) to a set of .java source files from the command line. Specifically, I want to replicate the effect of Eclipse's Source &gt; Clean Up operation (which can apply rules like removing unused imports, imports reordering, adding missing annotations, converting loops to enhanced for-loops, etc.) using a predefined Eclipse cleanup profile, xml or epf that contains cleanup rules like:</p>\n<pre><code>cleanup.add_generated_serial_version_id=false\ncleanup.add_missing_annotations=true\ncleanup.add_missing_deprecated_annotations=true\ncleanup.add_missing_methods=false\ncleanup.add_missing_nls_tags=false\ncleanup.add_missing_override_annotations=true\n</code></pre>\n<p>The behavior I'm looking for is something like running the formatter application from the command line <a href=\"https://help.eclipse.org/latest/index.jsp?topic=%2Forg.eclipse.jdt.doc.user%2Ftasks%2Ftasks-231.htm\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Running the Formatter Application</a></p>\n<p>Also trying to find a way to apply code templates programmatically like adding copyright comments at the beginning of the files using exported Eclipse template.</p>\n"
